{"parse":{"title":"Archangel Michael in Christian art","pageid":35501753,"revid":789626317,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Michael4.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Michael4.jpg/200px-Michael4.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"334\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Michael4.jpg/300px-Michael4.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/eb/Michael4.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"359\" data-file-height=\"600\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Michael4.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Statue of Archangel Michael at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Bonn\" title=\"University of Bonn\">University of Bonn</a>, slaying <a href=\"/wiki/Satan\" title=\"Satan\">Satan</a> as a <a href=\"/wiki/Dragon\" title=\"Dragon\">dragon</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Quis_ut_Deus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Quis ut Deus\">Quis ut Deus</a></i> is inscribed on his shield.</div></div></div>\n<p><b><a href=\"/wiki/Archangel_Michael\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Archangel Michael\">Archangel Michael</a></b> may be depicted in <a href=\"/wiki/Christian_art\" title=\"Christian art\">Christian art</a> alone or with other <a href=\"/wiki/Angels\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Angels\">angels</a> such as <a href=\"/wiki/Gabriel\" title=\"Gabriel\">Gabriel</a> or saints. Some depictions with Gabriel date back to the 8th century, e.g. the stone casket at <a href=\"/wiki/Mortain\" title=\"Mortain\">Notre Dame de Mortain</a> church in France.<sup id=\"cite_ref-rich141_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-rich141-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  He is very often present in scenes of the <a href=\"/wiki/Last_Judgement\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Last Judgement\">Last Judgement</a>, but few other specific scenes, so most images including him are devotional rather than narrative.  The angel who rescues <a href=\"/wiki/Shadrach,_Meshach,_and_Abednego\" title=\"Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego\">Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego</a> from the \"fiery furnace\" in the Book of <span class=\"nourlexpansion nowrap\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Daniel+3&amp;version=NIV\">Daniel Chapter 3</a></span> is usually regarded in Christian tradition as Michael; this is sometimes represented in <a href=\"/wiki/Early_Christian_art\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Early Christian art\">Early Christian art</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Eastern Orthodox\">Eastern Orthodox</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Icon\" title=\"Icon\">icons</a>, but rarely in later art of the Western church. \n</p><p>In most depictions Michael is represented as an angelic warrior, fully armed with helmet, sword, and shield,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cathenc_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cathenc-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> in the style of a Byzantine officer, which is typically found even in Western depictions, though some late-medieval ones have him in contemporary knightly armour.  Like other angels, in late-medieval Western art he may have what are known as <a href=\"/wiki/Feather_tights\" title=\"Feather tights\">feather tights</a>, with large feathers over most of his body, as on the <a href=\"/wiki/Holy_Thorn_Reliquary\" title=\"Holy Thorn Reliquary\">Holy Thorn Reliquary</a>.  He may be standing over a serpent, a dragon, or the defeated figure of Satan, whom he sometimes pierces with a lance.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cathenc_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cathenc-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The iconography of Michael slaying a serpent goes back to the early 4th century, when <a href=\"/wiki/Emperor_Constantine\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Emperor Constantine\">Emperor Constantine</a> defeated <a href=\"/wiki/Licinius\" title=\"Licinius\">Licinius</a> at the <a href=\"/wiki/Battle_of_Adrianople_(324)\" title=\"Battle of Adrianople (324)\">Battle of Adrianople</a> in 324 AD, not far from the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Michaelion\" title=\"Michaelion\">Michaelion</a></i>, a church dedicated to Archangel Michael.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Richard_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Richard-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Constantine felt that Licinius was an agent of Satan, and associated him with the <a href=\"/wiki/Serpent_(Bible)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Serpent (Bible)\">serpent</a> described in the <a href=\"/wiki/Book_of_Revelation\" title=\"Book of Revelation\">Book of Revelation</a> (<a href=\"https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Bible_(American_Standard)/Revelation#12:9\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikisource:Bible (American Standard)/Revelation\">12:9</a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> After the victory, Constantine commissioned a depiction of himself and his sons slaying Licinius represented as a serpent - a symbolism borrowed from the Christian teachings on the Archangel to whom he attributed the victory. A similar painting, this time with the Archangel Michael himself slaying a serpent then became a major art piece at the Michaelion and eventually lead to the standard <a href=\"/wiki/Iconography\" title=\"Iconography\">iconography</a> of Archangel Michael as a <a href=\"/wiki/Warrior_saint\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Warrior saint\">warrior saint</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Richard_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Richard-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In other depictions Michael may be holding a pair of scales in which he weighs the <a href=\"/wiki/Souls\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Souls\">souls</a> of the departed and may hold the <a href=\"/wiki/Book_of_Life\" title=\"Book of Life\">book of Life</a> (as in the <a href=\"/wiki/Book_of_Revelation\" title=\"Book of Revelation\">Book of Revelation</a>), to show that he takes part in the <a href=\"/wiki/Last_judgment\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Last judgment\">judgment</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-rich141_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-rich141-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Cathenc_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cathenc-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> However this form of depiction is less common than the slaying of the dragon.<sup id=\"cite_ref-rich141_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-rich141-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Michelangelo\" title=\"Michelangelo\">Michelangelo</a> depicted this scene on the altar wall of the <a href=\"/wiki/Sistine_Chapel\" title=\"Sistine Chapel\">Sistine Chapel</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The shield may bears the Latin inscription <i><a href=\"/wiki/Quis_ut_Deus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Quis ut Deus\">Quis ut Deus</a></i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Byzantine_art\" title=\"Byzantine art\">Byzantine art</a> Michael was often shown wearing the formal court robes and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Loros\" title=\"Loros\">loros</a></i> that were worn by the Emperor and his bodyguard on special occasions, rather than as a normal warrior who battled Satan or with scales for weighing souls on the <a href=\"/wiki/Day_of_Judgement\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Day of Judgement\">Day of Judgement</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The widely reproduced image of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Our_Mother_of_Perpetual_Help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Our Mother of Perpetual Help\">Our Mother of Perpetual Help</a></i>, an icon of the <a href=\"/wiki/Cretan_school\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cretan school\">Cretan school</a>, depicts Michael on the left carrying the lance and sponge of the <a href=\"/wiki/Crucifixion_of_Jesus\" title=\"Crucifixion of Jesus\">crucifixion of Jesus</a>, with <a href=\"/wiki/Gabriel\" title=\"Gabriel\">Gabriel</a> on the right side of <a href=\"/wiki/Madonna_and_Child\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Madonna and Child\">Mary and Jesus</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Eastern Orthodox\">Eastern Orthodox</a> depictions, there are three icons of the Archangel Michael in whose composition he is said to have personally intervened: Archangel Michael of Mantamados in <a href=\"/wiki/Mytilene\" title=\"Mytilene\">Mytilene</a>, Archangel Michael of <a href=\"/wiki/Panormitis\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Panormitis\">Panormitis</a> and Archangel Michael of <a href=\"/wiki/Nenita_(Greece)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nenita (Greece)\">Nenita</a>. Each of these icons is different.\n</p><p><br />\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Archangel_Michael_in_Christian_art&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Angels_in_art\" title=\"Angels in art\">Angels in art</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Gallery_of_art\">Gallery of art</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Archangel_Michael_in_Christian_art&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Gallery of art\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<dl><dd><i>For a larger gallery of art, please see</i>: <a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Archangel_Michael_structured_gallery\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"commons:Archangel Michael structured gallery\">Saint Michael art gallery</a>.</dd></dl>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg/80px-Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg\" width=\"80\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg/120px-Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg/160px-Byzantine_ivory_801.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2592\" data-file-height=\"3888\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Byzantine ivory, half of a <a href=\"/wiki/Diptych\" title=\"Diptych\">diptych</a>, early 6th century\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg/80px-St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg\" width=\"80\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg/120px-St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg/160px-St_Michael_La_Martorana_Palermo_2008-08-27.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2100\" data-file-height=\"3150\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Mosaic in Byzantine court dress, 12th century\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg/90px-H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg/135px-H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg/180px-H%C3%B4tel_Dieu_Altarbild.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"620\" data-file-height=\"827\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Weighing souls, from a 15th-century <i>Last Judgement</i>\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:ArchangelDossi.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/18/ArchangelDossi.jpg/68px-ArchangelDossi.jpg\" width=\"68\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/18/ArchangelDossi.jpg/102px-ArchangelDossi.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/18/ArchangelDossi.jpg/136px-ArchangelDossi.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"161\" data-file-height=\"283\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><i>The triumphant St. Michael</i>, by <a href=\"/wiki/Dosso_Dossi\" title=\"Dosso Dossi\">Dosso Dossi</a>, 16th century\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:ArchangelRubens.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d3/ArchangelRubens.jpg/80px-ArchangelRubens.jpg\" width=\"80\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d3/ArchangelRubens.jpg/120px-ArchangelRubens.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d3/ArchangelRubens.jpg/160px-ArchangelRubens.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"367\" data-file-height=\"550\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><i>St. Michael and fallen angels</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Rubens\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Rubens\">Rubens</a>, 17th century\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg/79px-Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg\" width=\"79\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg/119px-Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg/159px-Rublev_Arhangel_Mikhail.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1300\" data-file-height=\"1963\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Russian icon by <a href=\"/wiki/Andrei_Rublev\" title=\"Andrei Rublev\">Andrei Rublev</a>, c. 1408\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Mikharkhangel2.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Mikharkhangel2.jpg/89px-Mikharkhangel2.jpg\" width=\"89\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Mikharkhangel2.jpg/133px-Mikharkhangel2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Mikharkhangel2.jpg/178px-Mikharkhangel2.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1300\" data-file-height=\"1753\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Michael the Archangel and biblical scenes, Russian icon, c. 1410\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg/116px-Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg\" width=\"116\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg/174px-Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg/232px-Louvre_saint_michel_rf1427.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1732\" data-file-height=\"1791\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Early Gothic relief, France, 1125\u201350\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Paris_July_2011-24.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Paris_July_2011-24.jpg/84px-Paris_July_2011-24.jpg\" width=\"84\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Paris_July_2011-24.jpg/126px-Paris_July_2011-24.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/Paris_July_2011-24.jpg/168px-Paris_July_2011-24.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1880\" data-file-height=\"2676\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>St Michael's Fountain, on <a href=\"/wiki/Boulevard_Saint-Michel\" title=\"Boulevard Saint-Michel\">Boulevard Saint-Michel</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Paris\" title=\"Paris\">Paris</a>\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 